Array ([mode]=>parse_add[order]=>st[seq]=>10[product]=>i6[title]=>fix FilterSQL function[status]=>Active[details]=>function FilterSQL($s){
    debug_string(\"FilterSQL(s)\");
    debug_array(\"s\",$s);
    $result = array();
    foreach($s as $key=>$value){
        debug_string(\"key\",$key);
        debug_string(\"value\",$value);
        $filtered = $value;
        $filtered = str_replace(\"\\\\\",\"\\\\\\\\\",$filtered);
        $filtered = str_replace(\"\\\"\",\"\\\\\\\"\",$filtered);
        $filtered = str_replace(\"\'\",\"\\\'\",$filtered);
        $filtered = str_replace(\"\\n\",\"\\\\\\n\",$filtered);
        $filtered = str_replace(\"\\r\",\"\\\\\\r\",$filtered);
        $filtered = str_replace(\"\\x1a\",\"\\\\\\x1a\",$filtered);
        $filtered = str_replace(\"\\x00\",\"\\\\\\x00\",$filtered);
        $result[$key] = $filtered;
        debug_string(\"filtered value\",$result[$key]);
    }
    //$result = str_replace(\"\'\",\"\\\'\",$s);
    //$result = mysql_real_escape_string ($s);
    debug_array(\"result\",$result);
    return $result;
}

*record:
Array ([id]=>1059[seq]=>20[userno]=>1[title]=>change display to ignore people with fewer than N games played[details]=>N depends on the data set. For example, as I write this no one has played more than 4 or 5 games so to say "no one with less than 10 games counts" means we have no data at all.  So it should be by percentage. Something like "Only people who have been to 32% of the parties (4 in a year)" or "only people who are in the top 80% of people with respect to # of games" or something like that. 

In short, we always want to show a few players but it would be nice to show only those people who are serious players. 

Maybe we simply say, "here is the list of everyone (list A) and here is the list of people who have played more than 10 games (list b)" If list b is empty then we use list A. Eh, viola![done]=>0[productid]=>15[duration]=>0[hidden]=>0[taskdate]=>2009-01-24[donedate]=>[status]=>Active[delto]=>[todoTS]=>20100315081454)

*record:
Array ([id]=>571[seq]=>20[userno]=>1[title]=>verification function[details]=>The idea is to have a regular expression and a name in a database. like "phone number" and a regex that checks to make sure it's a phone number or "email" and regex that checks for that.
Then you have another database that has a name (or, actually, a number) that relates to the regex and a field name. Finally, we have a routine. The routine runs through the list of $PARAMS and checks them against the database of field names, creating a list of errors. Basically, we call that at the top of every program. 

A potential problem is the name space. One program's "name" may require a different regex than another program's name. But we want to be able to reuse field names and their regex (which means that for most programs you'll only have to actually write one or two regex's and get the rest of the verification system for free).
